Section section_01 (Chars 0–8927):
Section Summary: The author's interest in science and philosophy was sparked by reading Tyndall's "Discourse on The Scientific Use of the Imagination" and later Herbert Spencer's works. Spencer's philosophy of evolution and differentiation had a significant impact on the author, who saw it as a way to understand the universe and its complexities. The author was drawn to Spencer's idea that every active force produces more than one change, and that this principle could be applied to all aspects of life. Spencer's philosophy emphasized the universality of law and causation, and he is credited with widening the scope of scientific explanation to include the realm of mind and society. The author acknowledges that Spencer's philosophy is broader than just his ideas on life and mind, and that his contributions to philosophy include his sweeping formula for evolution and his emphasis on ubiquitous causes and the persistence of force.
